If two quantities are in the ratio $a:b$ and their combined total is $T$, then:
\begin{align*}
\text{First quantity} &= \frac{a}{a+b} \times T \\[4pt]
\text{Second quantity} &= \frac{b}{a+b} \times T
\end{align*}

This extends naturally to three or more parts: for a ratio $a:b:c$ with total $T$, each part is its share of $(a+b+c)$ multiplied by $T$.

**Percentage**: A percentage is a ratio expressed as a fraction of 100. “Per cent” literally means “per hundred.”
\begin{align*}
\text{Percentage} &= \frac{\text{Part}}{\text{Whole}} \times 100% \\[4pt]
\text{Part} &= \frac{\text{Percentage}}{100} \times \text{Whole}
\end{align*}

**Converting between forms**:
\begin{itemize}
    \item Percent to decimal: divide by 100.   e.g.\ $37% = 0.37$
    \item Decimal to percent: multiply by 100.   e.g.\ $0.625 = 62.5%$
    \item Fraction to percent: divide numerator by denominator, then multiply by 100.
\end{itemize}

